{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "6151e86350d1e84790633db4", "type": "numerical", "level": null, "category": null, "approximateTimeRequired": null, "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "source": "NTAS1", "classes": [], "exams": ["615d76b2c52ffa3c944600df"], "subjects": ["615d708dbd4a37c4058ee5a8"], "chapters": ["615d6fec2b295b085ab6eb92"], "topics": [], "concepts": [], "microConcepts": [], "questionLabels": [{"title": "NTA Abhyas Paper", "value": "91", "isVisible": true}], "previousYearPapers": [], "question": {"text": "A large sphere of mass&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>M</mi></math> is fixed at one position and two identical particles each of mass&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math>&nbsp;are kept on a line passing through the centre of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>M</mi></math> (see figure). The point masses are connected by a rigid massless rod of length <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math> and this assembly is free to move along the line connecting them. All three masses interact only through their mutual gravitational interaction. When the point mass nearer to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>M</mi></math> is at a distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>l</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>M</mi></math>, the tension in the rod is zero for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mfrac><mi>M</mi><mn>288</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>. The value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math> is<br />\r<br />\r<br />\r<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/nta_abhyas/jee_main/images/ci/image5-5173a529-60b6-4425-b1dc-89ce80a6f1c1.jpg\" style=\"max-width:100%; object-fit:contain\" style=\"height: 61px; width: 300px;\" />", "image": null}, "options": [], "correctValue": "7", "solution": {"text": "Due to gravitational interaction connected masses have some acceleration.<br /><br />Let both small masses are moving with acceleration 'a' towards larger mass M<br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/nta_abhyas/jee_main/images/ci/image6-db67c1cc-3cf9-4c0c-863a-38201940e80d.jpg\" style=\"max-width:100%; object-fit:contain\" style=\"height: 123px; width: 300px;\" /><br /><br />Force equation for mass nearer to a larger mass<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>a</mi></math> ...(i)<br /><br />Force equation for mass away from a larger mass<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>a</mi></math> ...(ii)<br /><br />From equation (i) &amp; (ii)<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>16</mn><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math><br />